  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3205756563" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3205756563" />
    <a title="Monica Hunter-Hart" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/61236285-monica-hunter-hart"><img alt="Monica Hunter-Hart" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1626326213p2/61236285.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3205756563?book_show_action=true">Jul 14, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Monica Hunter-Hart" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Monica Hunter-Hart" href="/user/show/61236285-monica-hunter-hart">Monica Hunter-Hart</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3205756563" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8251696608217861190">A truly outstanding feat of reporting and writing. Most of the book takes place in Iraq—Filkins was rarely stationary, it seems, but was constantly zig-zagging around the country for alternating visits to hotspots and remote areas and interviews with politicians, soldiers, contractors, and civilians of different religious, ethnic, and class backgrounds. The diversity of stories he illustrates is one of the book&apos;s greatest strengths.<br/><br/>Filkins knows how to craft a wallop of an ending for a vignette.</span>
  <span id="freeText8251696608217861190" style="display:none">A truly outstanding feat of reporting and writing. Most of the book takes place in Iraq—Filkins was rarely stationary, it seems, but was constantly zig-zagging around the country for alternating visits to hotspots and remote areas and interviews with politicians, soldiers, contractors, and civilians of different religious, ethnic, and class backgrounds. The diversity of stories he illustrates is one of the book's greatest strengths.<br /><br />Filkins knows how to craft a wallop of an ending for a vignette. He'll set a scene and describe its characters in vivid detail, point to clues of the unspoken dynamics at play, and deftly illustrate a central tension. Through his eyes, the reader watches it build or simmer. Then he'll abruptly end the scene at a moment when that tension is challenged—leaving a note of irony hanging, implying the ultimately incomprehensible complexity of the conflict and characters, and hinting at everything that he can't write, or know. For example, he ends one scene when a man embraces and kisses the leader of a militia he believes killed his brother, and another when an insurgent attack fails to come after marines have marked a series of tell-tale signs.<br /><br />Perhaps unsurprisingly, this is one of the most disturbing books I've ever read. It's so intense that I actually had to read it over a period of several years. I put it down for many months at a time when it became too much. Filkins doesn't hold back in describing absolutely horrific acts of violence and trauma, and few scenes transpire without them. The rawness is central to the book's importance.<br /><br />Filkins' voice generally comes across as both sober-minded and empathetic. Still, the book is not without the occasional sweeping statement that borders on exoticism towards Afghans, Iraqis, or their countries. I also had a few concerns about journalistic ethics here and there—he mentions paying a source for information at least once, which is usually considered very improper, but maybe war reporting involves a unique, more flexible set of rules? It was wild to learn that he didn't know Arabic, Pashto, Dari, or any other of the languages spoken around him, but instead used translators the whole time. It was probably justifiable to have a native guide when the stakes were extremely high and required a deep knowledge of culture and slang (for example, Filkins sometimes relied on translators to interpret subtle shifts in tone during an interview, to sense when it was no longer safe to continue the conversation). But still, it seems indefensible that he didn't learn ANY Arabic during his many years in Iraq. And I've always had somewhat mixed feelings about the ethics of employing fixers who assume the dangers that a journalist daren't face.<br /><br />Because of those issues, I'd give the book a 4.7 if I could. But overall, it is an extremely illuminating piece of journalism about these two wars. It's excruciating. It's mercilessly real. It's important.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8251696608217861190" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


